base:vancomycin a type:Product,
        type:Treatment ;
    rdfs:label "vancomycin" ;
    prop:approve_for base:the_United_States ;
    prop:change_over base:the_years ;
    prop:exhibit base:Journal_of_the_American_Chemical_Society ;
    prop:extractedFrom "\"A redesigned vancomycin engineered for dual D-Ala-D-ala And D-Ala-D-Lac binding exhibits potent antimicrobial activity against vancomycin-resistant bacteria\".",
        "\"Peripheral modifications of [Ψ[CH2NH]Tpg4]vancomycin with added synergistic mechanisms of action provide durable and potent antibiotics\".",
        """History
[edit]Vancomycin was first isolated in 1953 by a research team lead by chemist Edmund Kornfeld at Eli Lilly, from a soil sample provided by missionary William M. Bouw.""",
        "In recent years, the percentage of multidrug resistant (MDR) strains, namely the vancomycin-resistant enterococci (VRE), surged worldwide, leading the World Health Organization to include VRE among the ‘priority pathogens’ in the global list of antibiotic-resistant bacteria.7",
        """Medical uses
[edit]Vancomycin is indicated for the treatment of serious, life-threatening infections by Gram-positive bacteria of both aerobic and anaerobic types[16] that are unresponsive to other antibiotics.[17][18][19]
The increasing emergence of vancomycin-resistant enterococci (VRE) has resulted in the development of guidelines for use by the Centers for Disease Control Hospital Infection Control Practices Advisory Committee.""",
        "The first case of vancomycin-intermediate S. aureus (VISA) was reported in Japan in 1996;[141] but the first case of S. aureus truly resistant to glycopeptide antibiotics was only reported in 2002.[142]",
        """Therapeutic drug monitoring is also used for dose optimization of vancomycin in treating children.[56]
Target ranges for serum vancomycin concentrations have changed over the years.""",
        "Vancomycin was approved for medical use in the United States in 1958.[13]" ;
    prop:isolate_in base:1953,
        base:William_M_Bouw ;
    prop:provide base:the_National_Academy_of_Sciences ;
    prop:report_in base:Japan ;
    prop:result_in base:the_Centers_for_Disease_Control_Hospital_Infection_Control_Practices_Advisory_Committee ;
    prop:sourceUrl "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacteremia"^^xsd:anyURI,
